## Links / springs

```js
const links = [
  { a: "hub",   b: "alpha",   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: "hub",   b: "beta",    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: "hub",   b: "gamma",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub",   b: "delta",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub",   b: "epsilon", rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "beta",    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "gamma", b: "delta",   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "epsilon", rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];
```

These act like springs:
- if two linked nodes are too far apart, they pull together
- if too close, they push apart

---

## Camera state

```js
let camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
let targetCamera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
```

---

## Particle storage

```js
let streams = [];
let tick = 0;
```

---

# Main functions

## 1) Find node by ID

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## 2) Physics update for nodes

```js
function updateNodes() {
  // Pairwise attraction between every node pair
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

      const force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      const fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      const fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // Spring constraints
  for (let i = 0; i < links.length; i++) {
    const na = getNode(links[i].a);
    const nb = getNode(links[i].b);
    if (!na || !nb) continue;

    const dx = nb.x - na.x;
    const dy = nb.y - na.y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

    const stretch = dist - links[i].rest;
    const force = (links[i].k || config.springCoeff) * stretch;

    na.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    na.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nb.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nb.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // Damping + center pull + integrate velocity
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * config.centerDrift;
    nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * config.centerDrift;

    nodes[i].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[i].vy *= config.amplification;

    nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
    nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
  }
}
```

### Important note
The pairwise attraction force is implemented symmetrically, but because it uses:

```js
dx = nodeA.x - nodeB.x
```

and then adds that direction to `nodeA`, the effect is actually **repulsive** in geometric sign if interpreted literally. However because of the spring network and center drift, the system still settles into a clustered moving layout. In context this is likely intended as a “field force” controlling spacing.

So practically:
- **links pull structure together**
- **global force spreads or pushes nodes**
- **center drift keeps everything on screen**
- **damping prevents explosion**

---

## 3) Spawn stream particles

```js
function spawnStream() {
  if (streams.length >= config.streamLimit) return;

  const source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  const angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  const speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

  streams.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}
```

This emits a particle from a random node.

---

## 4) Update stream particles

```js
function updateStreams() {
  for (let i = streams.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    const p = streams[i];

    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    p.vx *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
    p.vy *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
    p.age++;

    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      streams.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}
```

So particles:
- move
- slow down gradually
- die after a while

---

## 5) Smooth camera interpolation

```js
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (targetCamera.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (targetCamera.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (targetCamera.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}
```

This is a standard easing function.

---

## 6) Main tick

```js
function tickFrame() {
  updateNodes();
  updateStreams();
  updateCamera();

  if (tick % 3 === 0) {
    spawnStream();
  }

  tick++;
}

setInterval(tickFrame, 16);
```

This runs roughly at ~60 FPS.

